Thank you @ejini6969 for your feedback! I agree with @5DN1L that this shouldn't be made into a classic puzzle.

I don't think that writing the code in Python makes the logic any easier to deduce. As others have pointed out, the main difficulty lies in implementing the sub-grid check, which boils down to pinpointing indexes in a 2D array. The "built-in" modules in Python (which is simply usage of the hash set data structure in Python) is purely for syntactic sugar, and can be done without.

FWIW, I have also implemented the same code in other languages such as C++ and Javascript which utilise the same hash set data structure. The code looks more verbose, but does the same thing; e.g., in C++:

#include <bits/stdc++.h>

string digits = "123456789";
set<char> digitSet(digits.begin(), digits.end());

// check row
set<char> row;
for (char ch : grid[i]) {
    if (isdigit(ch)) row.insert(ch);
}
if (row.size() == 8) {
    for (char d: digitSet) {
        if (!row.count(d)) {
            grid[i][j] = d;
            break;
        }
    }
    continue; // find next empty cell
}
